694
00:46:55,414 --> 00:46:57,075
Think you can make it?

695
00:46:57,249 --> 00:47:00,650
No. No, let's put her somewhere else.

696
00:47:06,190 --> 00:47:07,487
Good.

697
00:47:13,764 --> 00:47:15,493
Good.

698
00:47:19,336 --> 00:47:21,133
Like a doll.

699
00:47:24,275 --> 00:47:26,743
A doll with a sinus problem.

700
00:47:26,911 --> 00:47:31,007
We should put a pillow under her head.
I think that helps.

701
00:47:38,122 --> 00:47:39,851
Good.

702
00:47:41,292 --> 00:47:42,316
Much worse. Interesting.

703
00:47:46,548 --> 00:47:49,608
Do you think we should change
her clothes?

704
00:47:50,285 --> 00:47:53,618
Right. Don't know where that came from.

705
00:47:56,224 --> 00:47:57,714
Morning!

706
00:47:57,892 --> 00:48:01,225
Okay, not so loud.

707
00:48:03,398 --> 00:48:05,298
We didn't...

708
00:48:06,734 --> 00:48:09,464
Last... We didn't...

709
00:48:10,138 --> 00:48:12,072
It was a magical night.

710
00:48:12,240 --> 00:48:15,403
You made sounds I've never heard
a woman make before.

711
00:48:17,245 --> 00:48:19,304
We didn't...

712
00:48:19,647 --> 00:48:23,583
Not physically, but spiritually,
you were the best I've ever had.

713
00:48:25,753 --> 00:48:31,487
Whatever I did or didn't do
or said or didn't say...

714
00:48:31,659 --> 00:48:34,924
...it was all a little mistake.

715
00:48:35,663 --> 00:48:37,756
Well, nothing happened.

716
00:48:41,169 --> 00:48:43,262
That's a relief.

717
00:48:46,774 --> 00:48:49,607
I'm very busy. I have work to do.
You stay there and relax.

718
00:48:49,777 --> 00:48:52,610
Okay, I'll see you later.

719
00:48:57,452 --> 00:48:59,044
Lucy!

720
00:48:59,721 --> 00:49:00,779
Jesus, careful.

721
00:49:02,457 --> 00:49:04,891
There's a June Carver to see you.

722
00:49:05,126 --> 00:49:08,118
- June Carver, June Carver, June Carver.
- She went to Harvard.

723
00:49:08,296 --> 00:49:10,890
Yeah, well, so did I. Now look at me.

724
00:49:11,966 --> 00:49:13,957
Norman. Norman. Norman.

725
00:49:14,135 --> 00:49:15,932
- Norman!
- Sorry.

726
00:49:16,971 --> 00:49:19,531
She didn't have a strong background
in property law.

727
00:49:19,974 --> 00:49:23,137
She's down from Boston.
She only wants five minutes.

728
00:49:26,481 --> 00:49:28,312
Lucy.

729
00:49:28,483 --> 00:49:30,110
Lucy.

730
00:49:30,285 --> 00:49:31,877
This is June Carver.

731
00:49:33,221 --> 00:49:36,054
- Hi. It's a pleasure to meet you.
- You too.

732
00:49:36,224 --> 00:49:39,091
I don't have an appointment,
so feel free to throw me out.

733
00:49:39,260 --> 00:49:41,922
Well, I have security on standby.

734
00:49:42,096 --> 00:49:44,496
- Have a seat, please.
- Thanks.

735
00:49:44,832 --> 00:49:47,926
Did you have Criminal
with Professor Rappaport?

736
00:49:48,102 --> 00:49:50,798
- Oh, my God. I'm still shaking.
- Yeah.

737
00:49:50,972 --> 00:49:55,068
But I have to tell you, Miss Kelson,
you are a legend there.

738
00:49:55,243 --> 00:49:57,234
- Me?
- Editor of the <i>Law Review</i>.

739
00:49:57,412 --> 00:50:00,813
The articles you wrote on
the Richmond case. You're an inspiration.

740
00:50:01,182 --> 00:50:02,513
Well, yeah, I...

741
00:50:02,684 --> 00:50:05,847
I don't have a strong background
in property, but neither did you...

742
00:50:06,020 --> 00:50:09,251
...and look what you've accomplished.

743
00:50:09,424 --> 00:50:11,892
Well, you know, not that much, really.
I just...

744
00:50:12,060 --> 00:50:14,028
And there's this.

745
00:50:14,195 --> 00:50:15,685
I've never met Mr. Wade...

746
00:50:15,863 --> 00:50:18,696
...but in <i>Public Policy</i> magazine
he was interviewed...

747
00:50:18,866 --> 00:50:23,235
...about the challenges
of urban development and he said that...

748
00:50:23,404 --> 00:50:25,872
Is it ridiculous that I'm quoting this?

749
00:50:26,374 --> 00:50:27,500
No, not yet.

750
00:50:27,675 --> 00:50:31,941
"Architecture can shape a community
and turn strangers into neighbors.

751
00:50:32,113 --> 00:50:34,707
The right design for a park
makes people feel secure.

752
00:50:34,882 --> 00:50:37,578
A school building can be functional
and beautiful...

753
00:50:37,752 --> 00:50:41,051
...so kids feel engaged instead
of imprisoned."

754
00:50:41,222 --> 00:50:44,385
When I read that, it made me feel
I'd be working for a cause...

755
00:50:44,559 --> 00:50:45,651
...not just a company.

756
00:50:48,963 --> 00:50:51,022
Okay. You're hired.

757
00:50:51,399 --> 00:50:52,730
You're Mr. Wade.

758
00:50:52,900 --> 00:50:55,130
Someone has to be.
Although, I didn't write that.

759
00:50:55,303 --> 00:50:57,794
- Lucy did.
- No, you did. I remember being shocked.

760
00:50:58,239 --> 00:51:01,572
We've been working together so long
it's hard to remember who did what.

761
00:51:01,743 --> 00:51:04,234
- Sounds like an amazing team.
- George, do you mind...?

762
00:51:04,412 --> 00:51:09,145
I was saying how incredibly presumptuous
it was of me to come waltzing in here...

763
00:51:09,317 --> 00:51:11,478
...but Miss Kelson was nice enough
to see me.

764
00:51:11,653 --> 00:51:14,247
They're calling from
the Zoning Commission, Lucy.

765
00:51:14,422 --> 00:51:19,086
June, why don't we set up
a proper interview for tomorrow.

766
00:51:19,260 --> 00:51:24,027
It's all right. It's all right.
I could finish up with June.

767
00:51:24,198 --> 00:51:26,098
You're not coming to the meeting?

768
00:51:26,267 --> 00:51:28,735
- Have I ever come to the meeting?
- Good point.

769
00:51:29,270 --> 00:51:31,830
- Alrighty.
- Alrighty.

770
00:51:32,006 --> 00:51:34,338
Stupid plant. Do something
with this, will you?

771
00:51:34,509 --> 00:51:37,000
Absolutely. The ficus is fired.

772
00:51:37,178 --> 00:51:39,112
- Bye-bye.
- Bye.

773
00:51:39,280 --> 00:51:40,941
- So tell me...
- Yes.

774
00:51:41,115 --> 00:51:43,879
...first of all, you come from which...?
- Harvard.

775
00:51:44,519 --> 00:51:47,955
I was just wondering, are we still on
for the Mets game tonight?

776
00:51:48,122 --> 00:51:49,919
I love baseball.

777
00:51:50,191 --> 00:51:51,783
So are we still good?

778
00:51:51,959 --> 00:51:54,120
I'm a Red Sox fan, all the way.

779
00:51:54,295 --> 00:51:56,525
A Red Sox fan? Interesting.

780
00:51:56,698 --> 00:52:01,294
You obviously have a rich fantasy life
which is a fabulous plus in this company.

781
00:52:01,469 --> 00:52:05,462
Okay, that means you're a Boston girl,
probably a little bit Irish, Catholic...

782
00:52:05,640 --> 00:52:08,040
...big family, dirty, that kind of thing.
- Exactly.

783
00:52:08,209 --> 00:52:12,441
<i>Let's go, Mets! Let's go, Mets!</i>
<i>Let's go, Mets!</i>

784
00:52:12,613 --> 00:52:13,602
Strike him out!

785
00:52:13,781 --> 00:52:15,874
So, what did you think of June?

786
00:52:16,050 --> 00:52:17,108
Loved her. Loved her.

787
00:52:17,552 --> 00:52:19,110
Great. Yeah, me too.

788
00:52:19,287 --> 00:52:21,812
Yeah, she smiled obsequiously,
flattered me constantly.

789
00:52:21,989 --> 00:52:25,618
She'd have no problem picking out
an ottoman. Exactly what I'm looking for.

790
00:52:25,893 --> 00:52:28,054
A tad weak on the experience side, but...

791
00:52:28,229 --> 00:52:30,322
We went out for a drink,
talked for an hour.

792
00:52:30,498 --> 00:52:34,662
She's a very clever girl, you know. Sharp.

793
00:52:36,504 --> 00:52:39,337
So you guys went out for a drink and...

794
00:52:39,907 --> 00:52:43,308
She got nowhere to stay at the moment,
so I found her a room at the Grand.

795
00:52:43,478 --> 00:52:48,347
And I invited her to the company outing.
Turns out she's a useful tennis player.

796
00:52:48,850 --> 00:52:51,478
Well, I can swing a racket.

797
00:52:51,652 --> 00:52:53,677
Yes, I know, at my head.
I've experienced it.

798
00:52:53,855 --> 00:52:56,915
But listen, thanks to you
for finding her. Genius.

799
00:52:58,092 --> 00:52:59,992
Oh, God! It's gonna hit us!

800
00:53:00,361 --> 00:53:01,953
Get out of the way. Move!

801
00:53:03,931 --> 00:53:05,364
- Mike, you all right?
- Yeah.

802
00:53:05,533 --> 00:53:08,366
- Take it easy, the season just started.
- Thanks, George.

803
00:53:08,536 --> 00:53:10,299
Next time, go to a Yankees game.

804
00:53:17,278 --> 00:53:18,609
Hey, look, you're on TV.

805
00:53:22,884 --> 00:53:24,511
<i>I don't hear you.</i>
<i>I don't hear you.</i>

806
00:53:57,084 --> 00:53:58,415
Nice!

807
00:53:58,586 --> 00:54:00,486
- Nice one.
- Thank you.

808
00:54:16,604 --> 00:54:19,767
- Three-Iove.
- All right. Cool.

809
00:54:30,451 --> 00:54:32,009
Nice.

810
00:54:45,867 --> 00:54:47,858
Yeah!

811
00:54:48,035 --> 00:54:49,866
Mine, mine, mine! Okay!

812
00:54:50,037 --> 00:54:51,231
Come on!

813
00:55:07,622 --> 00:55:10,591
Lucy! Oh, my God, Lucy, are you okay?

814
00:55:10,758 --> 00:55:12,658
Do I have a concussion?
Ask me something.

815
00:55:13,561 --> 00:55:17,361
- Name all the Supreme Court Justices.
- Thomas, Ginsburg, Scalia, Stevens...

816
00:55:17,532 --> 00:55:20,501
...Kennedy, Rehnquist, Souter, Breyer,
O'Connor. Is that right?

817
00:55:21,002 --> 00:55:21,991
How should I know?

818
00:55:24,839 --> 00:55:26,238
Want some?

819
00:55:26,407 --> 00:55:28,170
Thanks, I really shouldn't.

820
00:55:28,342 --> 00:55:29,331
Okay.

821
00:55:35,516 --> 00:55:38,076
You think she's a natural redhead?

822
00:55:53,034 --> 00:55:56,197
You know, I was gonna give June a lift,
and then Howard offered.

823
00:55:56,370 --> 00:55:59,032
The fact that he liked her is
a big strike against her.

824
00:55:59,206 --> 00:56:03,939
Although I will say she's
an excellent tennis player. Very nice form.

825
00:56:04,111 --> 00:56:05,703
- Fantastically nice form.
- Oh, man.

826
00:56:05,880 --> 00:56:08,371
Incredibly lithe.

827
00:56:08,549 --> 00:56:11,109
What? I thought you liked her too.

828
00:56:11,285 --> 00:56:14,948
No, I jus... I think I just ate too much.

829
00:56:15,122 --> 00:56:17,886
Really? What did you have?

830
00:56:18,059 --> 00:56:22,393
Just a chili dog and some fries
and a soda...

831
00:56:22,563 --> 00:56:25,964
...and a bag of some little girl's
cookies...

832
00:56:26,133 --> 00:56:28,897
...and another chili dog
stuck in there somewhere.

833
00:56:29,070 --> 00:56:30,469
Okay.

834
00:56:30,638 --> 00:56:32,299
Let's try and take your mind off it.

835
00:56:32,473 --> 00:56:34,373
Okay.

836
00:56:34,542 --> 00:56:36,032
Heard from Ansel lately?

837
00:56:37,144 --> 00:56:39,078
I'm sorry.

838
00:56:39,246 --> 00:56:42,079
I've been thinking about this.
You should move on. Forget him.

839
00:56:42,249 --> 00:56:45,946
Plenty of other pebbles on the beach.
The world must be full of men who'd die...

840
00:56:46,120 --> 00:56:48,680
...to be with a compulsive
eater who can't fall in love.

841
00:56:48,856 --> 00:56:51,256
What? I've fallen in love.

842
00:56:51,425 --> 00:56:53,086
- Yeah?
- Yes!

843
00:56:53,260 --> 00:56:55,854
With whom, might I ask?

844
00:56:56,030 --> 00:56:57,088
And no pets.

845
00:57:04,839 --> 00:57:06,568
Billy Westhouse.

846
00:57:07,108 --> 00:57:08,336
Billy who?

847
00:57:08,509 --> 00:57:11,603
Westhouse. I knew him in high school.

848
00:57:11,779 --> 00:57:14,043
Did you tell Billy that you loved him?

849
00:57:14,215 --> 00:57:18,618
Did you say, "Billy, I love you"?

850
00:57:29,530 --> 00:57:31,020
Goodness!

851
00:57:31,198 --> 00:57:32,358
It's not funny.

852
00:57:32,533 --> 00:57:34,467
Sorry.

853
00:57:35,469 --> 00:57:38,131
That last chili dog is really barking.

854
00:57:40,490 --> 00:57:42,424
It's not perfect timing, I must say.

855
00:57:46,496 --> 00:57:47,690
We'll be in the city in 20 minutes.

856
00:57:47,864 --> 00:57:51,061
I don't have 20 seconds!
I feel like I swallowed a cruise missile.

857
00:57:54,237 --> 00:57:55,431
What...? What am I? 5 years old?

858
00:57:58,074 --> 00:58:00,907
- It's only a Volvo.
- Well, people just don't go in Volvos!

859
00:58:01,077 --> 00:58:03,477
- I'll buy you another Volvo.
- No!

860
00:58:03,646 --> 00:58:06,240
That'll be the only thing you'll ever
remember about me.

861
00:58:06,416 --> 00:58:09,476
I'll be the woman who went
on the front seat!

862
00:58:09,652 --> 00:58:12,086
That would be hard to forget.

863
00:58:16,993 --> 00:58:19,587
Okay, I have an idea. See that RV?

864
00:58:20,763 --> 00:58:22,890
- Yes.
- That is our target.

865
00:58:23,266 --> 00:58:25,291
Can you make it?
Therein lies your salvation.

866
00:58:25,468 --> 00:58:27,163
- No.
- Yes, it's an excellent idea.

867
00:58:27,337 --> 00:58:30,829
- It's unclean! I can hold it!
- It's a brain wave. Out of the car!

868
00:58:31,007 --> 00:58:36,536
I can hold it! George, I can hold it!
I'm holding it! I'm fine, I can hold it!

869
00:58:36,946 --> 00:58:42,680
No! No, no, George, I don't want...
I'm not going. I'm holding!

870
00:58:47,056 --> 00:58:49,047
Hi there!

871
00:58:59,702 --> 00:59:02,034
- You all right?
- Yes.

872
00:59:03,373 --> 00:59:04,362
- Okay?
- Yeah, I'm good.

873
00:59:04,541 --> 00:59:06,873
- You all right?
- I'm good.

874
00:59:07,043 --> 00:59:08,374
- What?
- My ankle. My ankle.

875
00:59:09,712 --> 00:59:11,976
No! No, no! Oh, God! No!

876
00:59:14,484 --> 00:59:15,951
Hi, there!

877
00:59:18,321 --> 00:59:20,152
Oh, God!

878
00:59:22,825 --> 00:59:24,417
Excuse me. Sorry to bother you.

879
00:59:24,594 --> 00:59:27,995
I'm not insane, but my friend needs to use
a bathroom. It's an emergency.

880
00:59:28,164 --> 00:59:30,155
- I'll give you $100.
- A thousand!

881
00:59:30,333 --> 00:59:31,493
Okay.

882
00:59:31,668 --> 00:59:33,158
Thank you. Very sweet of you.

883
00:59:33,336 --> 00:59:35,167
Thank you.

884
01:00:07,604 --> 01:00:10,300
Clean, clean, clean.

885
01:00:11,207 --> 01:00:12,299
Where are you guys from?

886
01:00:12,875 --> 01:00:17,335
Well, Kentucky originally,
but now this is pretty much home.

887
01:00:23,453 --> 01:00:24,545
Come here, babies.

888
01:00:24,721 --> 01:00:26,348
Hurry!

889
01:00:28,458 --> 01:00:31,791
What kind of mileage do you get
out of this thing? It's an RV, right?

890
01:00:31,961 --> 01:00:34,452
A recreational vehicle?

891
01:00:34,897 --> 01:00:37,297
Traffic's moving.

892
01:00:37,467 --> 01:00:40,027
Hold it! Hold it! Hold it! Hold it one sec!

893
01:00:40,203 --> 01:00:42,728
Honey, how are you doing?
Are you nearly ready?

894
01:00:42,905 --> 01:00:44,805
Kill me!

895
01:00:51,147 --> 01:00:53,172
Look at that poor jerk.

896
01:00:53,349 --> 01:00:56,147
Yes, poor jerk.

897
01:00:56,919 --> 01:00:58,978
Whoa, Nelly.

898
01:01:04,327 --> 01:01:06,261
George, where's the car?

899
01:01:06,429 --> 01:01:08,260
I'm sure it's been safely towed by now.

900
01:01:08,431 --> 01:01:10,831
Oh, God! George, George, George!

901
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:15,198
Don't worry, don't worry! In many ways,
it was the perfect end to the day.

902
01:01:15,371 --> 01:01:17,498
Except for those poor children
in the trailer.

903
01:01:17,674 --> 01:01:20,268
They actually looked quite frightened.

904
01:01:21,511 --> 01:01:23,342
Don't worry, I won't tell anyone.

905
01:01:23,513 --> 01:01:27,609
Once it's published in the company
newsletter, there'd be absolutely no point.

906
01:01:28,851 --> 01:01:32,287
All right, I'll call for a lift.

907
01:01:33,690 --> 01:01:36,124
Would you like to have
your nails done?

908
01:01:36,359 --> 01:01:38,190
A Hollywood tan, perhaps?

909
01:02:26,375 --> 01:02:29,538
God, it is such a beautiful city.

910
01:02:29,979 --> 01:02:32,140
And my favorite building of all time.
Look at that.

911
01:02:32,348 --> 01:02:35,146
Nirosta steel, sunburst tower,
gleaming gargoyles...

912
01:02:35,318 --> 01:02:37,980
...all designed by a man called
William Van Alen...

913
01:02:38,154 --> 01:02:40,122
...obsessed with beating
his former partner...

914
01:02:40,289 --> 01:02:43,622
...who was building the
Bank of Manhattan tower at 927 feet.

915
01:02:43,793 --> 01:02:47,729
So Van Alen announced
the Chrysler Building at 925 feet...

916
01:02:47,897 --> 01:02:51,924
...and then surreptitiously assembled
the 180-foot mast inside the tower...

917
01:02:52,101 --> 01:02:55,036
...and only revealed it after
the bank tower had been completed...

918
01:02:55,204 --> 01:02:57,900
...giving Van Alen the tallest building
for three months...

919
01:02:58,074 --> 01:03:00,668
...until of course...
- Until the Empire State Building.

920
01:03:05,748 --> 01:03:09,844
All right, please give me the name
of Van Alen's former partner.

921
01:03:11,287 --> 01:03:14,051
Who is H. Craig Severance?

922
01:03:15,792 --> 01:03:21,924
- I find you annoying.
- Yes, I'm sure you do.

923
01:03:24,167 --> 01:03:28,160
But it is pretty amazing what dreams
and lots of money can do, isn't it?

924
01:03:28,905 --> 01:03:30,463
Yes, it is.

925
01:03:31,040 --> 01:03:34,976
- And you know you're part of that, George.
- Yes, I am.

926
01:03:35,278 --> 01:03:39,078
All you have to do is use your power
for good instead of evil.

927
01:03:40,516 --> 01:03:42,040
If only I would.

928
01:03:44,554 --> 01:03:46,146
Listen...

929
01:03:46,556 --> 01:03:50,185
...I'm very sorry that these last couple
of months have been unbearable for you.

930
01:03:50,760 --> 01:03:53,888
Not at all.
Unbearable would have been bearable.

931
01:03:54,063 --> 01:03:58,329
Then I suppose it's a good thing
that your two weeks are almost up.

932
01:03:59,235 --> 01:04:00,759
This is it.

933
01:04:00,937 --> 01:04:04,236
I'll do the Children's League benefit.
I'll make sure June is set up.

934
01:04:04,407 --> 01:04:06,705
I'll take a pass at your speech
for the groundbreaking...

935
01:04:06,876 --> 01:04:08,901
...and I'll be out of your life forever.

936
01:04:09,245 --> 01:04:11,042
Great.

937
01:04:11,214 --> 01:04:13,205
Super.

938
01:04:34,003 --> 01:04:37,234
- Hi.
- Hey, hey.

939
01:04:37,874 --> 01:04:41,332
- I have tennis elbow from the other day.
- Oh, yes?

940
01:04:41,510 --> 01:04:47,574
- Lucy has tennis forehead. Much worse.
- Oh, no. I still feel terrible about that.

941
01:04:47,950 --> 01:04:50,009
Thank God she looks okay.

942
01:04:50,186 --> 01:04:53,314
Especially with that big benefit
you're all going to tonight.

943
01:04:53,489 --> 01:04:55,923
- What was it again?
- It's a benefit...

944
01:04:56,092 --> 01:04:59,323
...for the New York Children's League.
Lucy makes us give lots of money...

945
01:04:59,495 --> 01:05:02,396
...to help society and get a tax break.
Brilliant.

946
01:05:02,565 --> 01:05:04,863
- Sounds exciting.
- It would be almost impossible...

947
01:05:05,034 --> 01:05:09,494
...to tell you how boring it is.
Largely because it would be too boring.

948
01:05:10,072 --> 01:05:15,806
Well, boring to you might be scintillating
for a girl from Plainview, Wisconsin.

949
01:05:15,978 --> 01:05:17,343
See you later.

950
01:05:17,513 --> 01:05:19,310
What about, if you're not busy...

951
01:05:19,715 --> 01:05:23,014
...a bunch of us are going,
do you want to come and be bored?

952
01:05:24,387 --> 01:05:26,719
I'd love to.

953
01:05:28,391 --> 01:05:31,292
- All right. See you later.
- Okay.

954
01:05:37,500 --> 01:05:39,730
Oh, good. These need to go to Accounting.

955
01:05:39,902 --> 01:05:42,462
- The loan agreements need to be notarized.
- I got it.

956
01:05:42,638 --> 01:05:46,472
- Here's the Zoning Commission reports.
- Now you can start with the appraisals...

957
01:05:46,642 --> 01:05:48,701
Actually,
I don't know how much time I have.

958
01:05:48,878 --> 01:05:51,870
George sort of asked me
to go to the benefit with him tonight.

959
01:05:54,350 --> 01:05:55,840
Great.

960
01:05:56,018 --> 01:05:59,681
I just have to figure out what to wear.
I don't have anything.

961
01:06:01,057 --> 01:06:04,993
- "I don't have anything."
- God, she's nice.

962
01:06:09,065 --> 01:06:11,431
No, they're very good muffins.
They just need more fat.

963
01:06:11,600 --> 01:06:14,228
George, sign these
or we default on five different loans.

964
01:06:14,403 --> 01:06:16,098
- Take care.
- Well, hang on. Hang on.

965
01:06:16,272 --> 01:06:18,570
- I need to go over my speech.
- Sorry. I gotta run.

966
01:06:18,741 --> 01:06:21,301
We'll pick you up at eight
and go through it in the car.

967
01:06:21,477 --> 01:06:23,445
I asked June to come.
Hope that's all right.

968
01:06:23,612 --> 01:06:26,672
Oh, that's dandy, but I don't need a ride.
Thanks.

969
01:06:33,422 --> 01:06:35,014
- Hello, Howard.
- <i>George...</i>

970
01:06:35,191 --> 01:06:37,523
<i>... I just received new estimates</i>
<i>on Island Towers.</i>

971
01:06:37,693 --> 01:06:39,388
<i>Costs are skyrocketing.</i>

972
01:06:39,695 --> 01:06:42,459
<i>It will be cheaper to just knock down</i>
<i>the community center.</i>

973
01:06:42,631 --> 01:06:44,064
What are you talking about?

974
01:06:44,233 --> 01:06:46,326
We only got the job because we said
we'd keep it.

975
01:06:46,502 --> 01:06:49,198
- <i>We said we intended to keep the center.</i>
- No wait. You can't...

976
01:06:49,372 --> 01:06:51,738
This is nonsense.
You can't just decide unilaterally.

977
01:06:51,907 --> 01:06:53,204
- I'm coming over.
- <i>George.</i>

978
01:06:53,376 --> 01:06:56,834
<i>I want to take a nap before the benefit.</i>
<i>It's all very simple.</i>

979
01:06:57,380 --> 01:06:59,507
Why can't we just build the towers
over the center?

980
01:06:59,682 --> 01:07:01,877
<i>Because it will eat away our profits.</i>

981
01:07:02,051 --> 01:07:04,542
<i>There's to be a groundbreaking ceremony</i>
<i>at Coney Island...</i>

982
01:07:04,720 --> 01:07:06,950
<i>... with our friend Assemblyman Perez.</i>

983
01:07:07,123 --> 01:07:09,614
<i>All I need</i>
<i>is one of your charming speeches.</i>

984
01:07:09,792 --> 01:07:11,419
Well, you're not gonna get one.

985
01:07:11,761 --> 01:07:13,058
I need you there.

986
01:07:13,229 --> 01:07:16,357
- I have to consult my schedule.
- No, you won't, George. It's your job.

987
01:07:16,532 --> 01:07:20,332
You're the public face of the company.
They don't want to see me.

988
01:07:20,503 --> 01:07:23,529
I can't for the life of me think why not.
You're magnificent.

989
01:07:24,540 --> 01:07:27,703
Look, whatever we lose on this deal,
I'm in for half.

990
01:07:27,877 --> 01:07:30,175
You'll be in for nothing
at the rate you're going.

991
01:07:30,346 --> 01:07:34,612
Expensive divorces, poolside parties
at the hotel for 1000 people...

992
01:07:34,784 --> 01:07:38,242
...including fireworks
and a performance by Sting.

993
01:07:38,421 --> 01:07:39,945
That was one special night.

994
01:07:40,122 --> 01:07:44,058
It was Wendy the concierge's farewell bash
and a very good party if I say so myself.

995
01:07:44,827 --> 01:07:48,126
Look, I know you don't have a clue,
but the economy is not what it was.

996
01:07:50,666 --> 01:07:53,999
Everything we've got, all of it, could go.

997
01:07:54,236 --> 01:07:56,397
Faster than you can imagine.

998
01:07:57,373 --> 01:08:00,069
We need this built.

999
01:08:00,876 --> 01:08:03,743
You're our closer
and you will help me close this deal...

1000
01:08:03,913 --> 01:08:07,405
...or I will fire you
and take all your stock options.

1001
01:08:07,583 --> 01:08:10,882
And I can't bear to see you like that,
George.

1002
01:08:11,053 --> 01:08:13,954
You will help me close this deal, George,
won't you?

1003
01:08:16,258 --> 01:08:18,123
I'm surprised you have to ask.

1004
01:08:18,994 --> 01:08:21,462
I wasn't really asking.

1005
01:08:23,466 --> 01:08:27,402
- You should have gone with George.
- Well, he asked June.

1006
01:08:27,570 --> 01:08:31,973
- Not exclusively. He asked you too.
- He asked me too?

1007
01:08:32,141 --> 01:08:35,201
How many women should a man
take to dinner? Maybe in Utah.

1008
01:08:35,377 --> 01:08:38,278
- So you're gonna go alone?
- Sure, why not?

1009
01:08:38,614 --> 01:08:40,445
Hey, I think it's great.

1010
01:08:40,616 --> 01:08:43,176
I was always too scared
to go anywhere alone.

1011
01:08:43,352 --> 01:08:48,221
Then I got married.
Now I'll never be alone again.

1012
01:09:04,807 --> 01:09:07,833
Check out this situation.
You two kids have fun.

1013
01:09:08,010 --> 01:09:09,671
All right.

1014
01:09:10,613 --> 01:09:14,140
Howard. Helen, how are you?

1015
01:09:14,316 --> 01:09:16,546
Mr. and Mrs. Wade, good evening.

1016
01:09:19,455 --> 01:09:20,979
- I hate these things.
- Ridiculous.

1017
01:09:21,157 --> 01:09:23,523
Why can't we just give the money
and be done with it?

1018
01:09:23,859 --> 01:09:25,884
Yes, that'd be fun.
Who wants a drink?

1019
01:09:26,061 --> 01:09:28,154
- I'd love some champagne.
- We don't want anything.

1020
01:09:28,330 --> 01:09:30,321
- I'll have a Scotch.
- Great.

1021
01:09:30,499 --> 01:09:33,525
I'll be right back
with one of the promotional bottles.

1022
01:09:36,705 --> 01:09:38,605
- Wade.
- Trump.

1023
01:09:38,841 --> 01:09:42,572
- I hear Kelson finally dumped you.
- Not exactly, no.

1024
01:09:42,745 --> 01:09:46,112
We came to a mutual understanding that
she couldn't bear me for another second.

1025
01:09:46,282 --> 01:09:47,681
So who's the new chief counsel?

1026
01:09:47,850 --> 01:09:50,546
If she's any good,
I'm gonna steal her away.

1027
01:09:51,053 --> 01:09:53,214
I doubt it. She seems quite Ioyal to me.

1028
01:09:53,389 --> 01:09:55,789
- Let me be the judge of that.
- All right.

1029
01:09:55,958 --> 01:09:58,324
I'm not intimidated.
I'll even lead you to her.

1030
01:09:58,494 --> 01:10:00,826
She's over there somewhere.

1031
01:11:08,897 --> 01:11:10,865
Good evening.

1032
01:11:11,367 --> 01:11:13,232
Good evening.

1033
01:11:15,738 --> 01:11:17,433
Well, you look... I...

1034
01:11:17,873 --> 01:11:20,239
I... You...

1035
01:11:20,409 --> 01:11:24,243
- I can't wait to hear your speech.
- Yeah.

1036
01:11:24,680 --> 01:11:27,114
No, it's just you look absolutely...

1037
01:11:28,384 --> 01:11:29,681
...surprising.

1038
01:11:30,819 --> 01:11:34,687
Well, you haven't seen
the whole outfit yet.

1039
01:11:38,594 --> 01:11:42,428
You see, ordinarily that would suit you
extremely well, but...

1040
01:11:47,636 --> 01:11:49,729
Well, tonight you're...

1041
01:11:52,541 --> 01:11:54,304
I'm just...

1042
01:11:58,981 --> 01:12:00,744
- Lucy, hey.
- Hi.

1043
01:12:00,916 --> 01:12:04,977
- Wow. I love your dress.
- Thank you.

1044
01:12:05,154 --> 01:12:08,749
- And you look very beautiful.
- No.

1045
01:12:11,527 --> 01:12:15,691
- I'm sorry, was I interrupting something?
- No, no. We were just...

1046
01:12:18,100 --> 01:12:19,533
...going over my speech.

1047
01:12:20,703 --> 01:12:23,695
Right. Work, work, work.

1048
01:12:24,039 --> 01:12:26,564
Howard wants me to revise
the Island Towers proposal...

1049
01:12:26,742 --> 01:12:28,835
...now that we're tearing down
the community center.

1050
01:12:29,078 --> 01:12:33,777
- I could really use your help with that.
- I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

1051
01:12:36,518 --> 01:12:38,611
George, can I please talk to you
for a second?

1052
01:12:38,787 --> 01:12:42,780
Hang on. They're about to shoot a man
out of a cannon into a vat of ice cream.

1053
01:12:42,958 --> 01:12:44,653
George.

1054
01:12:53,268 --> 01:12:54,496
I don't care about Howard.

1055
01:12:58,573 --> 01:13:01,440
No community center. I see. Okay.

1056
01:13:05,580 --> 01:13:07,514
We do give millions to charities.

1057
01:13:09,584 --> 01:13:10,676
So that justifies lying.

1058
01:13:10,852 --> 01:13:14,117
Since when is helping people
and telling the truth mutually exclusive?

1059
01:13:14,289 --> 01:13:16,382
- You promised me.
- Oh, here we go.

1060
01:13:16,558 --> 01:13:19,493
You said you needed me to tell you
when you were being a schmuck.

1061
01:13:19,661 --> 01:13:23,119
It's frankly none of your business, is it?
You don't work here anymore!

1062
01:13:23,298 --> 01:13:26,392
I cannot believe you won't even try
to be the person you could be.

1063
01:13:26,568 --> 01:13:28,160
- This is the person I could be.
- No.

1064
01:13:28,336 --> 01:13:31,362
You think you're second-rate
and there's nothing you can do.

1065
01:13:31,539 --> 01:13:35,134
And I never believed it until right now.
This minute.

1066
01:13:35,877 --> 01:13:38,937
This is the first time in a year
that I really don't like you.

1067
01:13:41,015 --> 01:13:44,644
I haven't liked me for longer than that.
And I'm not crazy about you right now.

1068
01:13:44,819 --> 01:13:47,344
Why don't you go and be the person
you're supposed to be.

1069
01:13:47,989 --> 01:13:51,015
Oh, good. I see the mature part
of the evening has begun.

1070
01:13:51,192 --> 01:13:53,422
Oh, buzz off, bozo.

1071
01:13:54,228 --> 01:13:58,096
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>
<i>the ice cream is ready.</i>

1072
01:13:58,266 --> 01:14:01,133
<i>Here comes the topping.</i>

1073
01:14:10,478 --> 01:14:15,438
George, thanks again.
This was a spectacular evening.

1074
01:14:15,984 --> 01:14:19,147
I can't wait to tell my family who I met.

1075
01:14:19,320 --> 01:14:21,447
Why? Who did you meet?

1076
01:14:21,623 --> 01:14:23,488
You.

1077
01:14:26,728 --> 01:14:29,891
- What?
- The elevator.

1078
01:14:33,034 --> 01:14:35,764
- Evening.
- Evening.

1079
01:14:43,011 --> 01:14:45,104
- How's your room, by the way?
- Amazing.

1080
01:14:45,279 --> 01:14:51,548
- But I want to pay you back with interest.
- Don't be ridiculous. I don't need interest.

1081
01:14:54,555 --> 01:14:57,023
Well, this is me.

1082
01:14:57,225 --> 01:15:00,058
So good night.

1083
01:15:00,228 --> 01:15:02,128
Yeah, good night.

1084
01:15:03,331 --> 01:15:09,167
- I had a wonderful time.
- Good. I'm very glad about that.

1085
01:15:11,773 --> 01:15:14,173
So good night.

1086
01:15:16,577 --> 01:15:18,568
Yes, good night.

1087
01:15:32,994 --> 01:15:38,432
It's all right. I own the hotel.
Your breakfast is complimentary.

1088
01:15:49,544 --> 01:15:51,205
Gorgeous.

1089
01:15:52,180 --> 01:15:58,415
I know it's weird living in a hotel
but it somehow has a very homey feel.

1090
01:15:59,320 --> 01:16:01,845
Would you like something
from the minibar?

1091
01:16:02,256 --> 01:16:04,224
Maybe a beer.

1092
01:16:04,459 --> 01:16:06,120
Right.

1093
01:16:15,036 --> 01:16:19,097
Wow, chess. I love chess.

1094
01:16:20,908 --> 01:16:23,103
You know what I love
even more than chess?

1095
01:16:25,480 --> 01:16:26,742
Pokemon?

1096
01:16:27,815 --> 01:16:29,282
Strip chess.

1097
01:16:30,952 --> 01:16:33,614
Yes, that is a very good game.

1098
01:16:43,865 --> 01:16:46,299
George?
We need to finish this conversation please...

1099
01:16:46,467 --> 01:16:49,527
- Lucy.
- Oh, June. Hi.

1100
01:16:49,704 --> 01:16:53,663
- Lucy, hi.
- Wow. Wow. Great slip.

1101
01:16:53,841 --> 01:16:57,402
- That's a great dress.
- Oh, you know, same one as before.

1102
01:16:57,578 --> 01:17:01,309
All right. Break's over.
I'm gonna capture your bish...

1103
01:17:03,718 --> 01:17:05,151
- Hi.
- Hi.

1104
01:17:13,261 --> 01:17:15,195
We were just playing a little chess.

1105
01:17:18,866 --> 01:17:20,390
And doing some laundry.

1106
01:17:20,568 --> 01:17:22,502
Oh, well, that's okay.

1107
01:17:22,670 --> 01:17:26,128
'Cause I was just about to go off
and have some sex myself.

1108
01:17:26,307 --> 01:17:28,366
I mean, not by myself...

1109
01:17:28,543 --> 01:17:33,037
...but with somebody. Somebody else.

1110
01:17:33,815 --> 01:17:36,784
Oh, you don't know him.
He's in my apartment.

1111
01:17:36,951 --> 01:17:38,885
Yeah, in my bed.

1112
01:17:40,721 --> 01:17:43,087
His name is Barry. Yeah.

1113
01:17:43,257 --> 01:17:46,351
Barry in my bed. Okay, bye.

1114
01:17:50,865 --> 01:17:53,060
That was embarrassing.

1115
01:18:26,934 --> 01:18:28,458
- Hey.
- Hey.

1116
01:18:28,636 --> 01:18:31,400
- What's wrong?
- Thanks for your shoes.

1117
01:18:32,607 --> 01:18:35,337
Hold on, lady. Look at me.
What happened?

1118
01:18:35,509 --> 01:18:38,000
- Nothing.
- Something happened.

1119
01:18:38,179 --> 01:18:41,671
I've known you since Brownies,
I've never seen you cry.

1120
01:18:41,849 --> 01:18:44,374
Except when Bush won.

1121
01:18:45,186 --> 01:18:47,154
Which Bush?

1122
01:18:47,321 --> 01:18:52,554
- Both of them. So maybe you cried twice.
- This is a different George.

1123
01:18:52,727 --> 01:18:54,388
I'm sorry.

1124
01:18:54,562 --> 01:18:57,224
It's not supposed to be like this.

1125
01:18:58,399 --> 01:18:59,832
Maybe it is.

1126
01:19:01,035 --> 01:19:05,335
Maybe it's like the philosopher
Sri Yogananda says:

1127
01:19:05,506 --> 01:19:11,138
"Only that which is the other,
gives us fully unto ourselves."

1128
01:19:12,580 --> 01:19:16,744
Look. I had to fight for Tom.
It was the best thing I ever did.

1129
01:19:16,918 --> 01:19:17,976
Really?

1130
01:19:18,853 --> 01:19:21,151
Everything okay?

1131
01:19:21,322 --> 01:19:27,318
- Not now. Everything is not about you!
- Okay.

1132
01:19:49,350 --> 01:19:52,649
Quiet, everyone. Quiet down, please.

1133
01:19:52,820 --> 01:19:54,515
Thank you.

1134
01:19:55,089 --> 01:20:00,618
I have a little poem I wrote for you, Lucy.
If you could just come up here.

1135
01:20:01,262 --> 01:20:02,889
Please.

1136
01:20:11,038 --> 01:20:13,973
- You ready for this?
- Rhyme away.

1137
01:20:16,510 --> 01:20:19,001
<i>A rolling stone gathers no moss</i>

1138
01:20:19,580 --> 01:20:20,911
<i>So</i>

1139
01:20:21,716 --> 01:20:25,618
<i>You're leaving</i>
<i>With your antacids and floss</i>

1140
01:20:25,953 --> 01:20:31,152
<i>Our hair perhaps we will toss</i>
<i>But we are at a loss</i>

1141
01:20:31,325 --> 01:20:37,286
<i>Because you are the world's best boss</i>

1142
01:20:46,474 --> 01:20:48,874
Well, that was a very nice speech
you just made...

1143
01:20:49,043 --> 01:20:55,414
...and I'm going to really miss everyone
here at Wade.

1144
01:20:57,251 --> 01:20:59,981
There are a million memories
I wouldn't trade...

1145
01:21:00,154 --> 01:21:06,559
...and if you ever get accused of murder,
you can find me at Legal Aid.

1146
01:21:11,098 --> 01:21:13,931
- What was that?
- Well, it was the same thing you just did.

1147
01:21:14,101 --> 01:21:17,730
Bye. Bye. Thank you.
Thank you very much. Nice...

1148
01:21:17,905 --> 01:21:19,065
- Bye.
- Bye.

1149
01:21:19,240 --> 01:21:21,299
I'll really miss
all your comprehensive reports.

1150
01:21:21,475 --> 01:21:23,204
Me too. Me too.

1151
01:21:23,377 --> 01:21:26,471
Lucy. Thank you so much for everything.

1152
01:21:26,981 --> 01:21:29,279
No problem.
Well, good luck with everything.

1153
01:21:29,450 --> 01:21:32,419
And I'm sorry about last night.
That was awkward.

1154
01:21:32,653 --> 01:21:37,647
- Oh, not at all. Brian was unbelievable.
- I thought it was Barry.

1155
01:21:38,826 --> 01:21:43,729
Well, Barry was first, and then
it was Brian, and it was just crowded.

1156
01:21:45,332 --> 01:21:48,028
- I almost forgot my stapler.
- Is that...? Oh, God.

1157
01:21:48,202 --> 01:21:50,136
- What?
- Never mind.

1158
01:21:50,304 --> 01:21:53,068
- No, no. What?
- Well, it's just that technically...

1159
01:21:53,240 --> 01:21:57,176
...the stapler belongs to the company.
- That's right.

1160
01:21:57,344 --> 01:21:59,278
But... No, you know what? Whatever.

1161
01:21:59,447 --> 01:22:02,644
It's... The stapler just goes way back
with me. And I...

1162
01:22:02,817 --> 01:22:05,445
Well, no, no. You keep it.
It'll be our little secret.

1163
01:22:05,619 --> 01:22:07,678
- Really?
- Yeah.

1164
01:22:07,855 --> 01:22:09,880
Great, thank you. Thank you very much.

1165
01:22:10,057 --> 01:22:11,547
I guess I have kind of earned it...

1166
01:22:11,725 --> 01:22:14,489
...working here 18 hours a day,
seven days a week.

1167
01:22:14,662 --> 01:22:17,529
Wow. Guess that makes you a workaholic.

1168
01:22:17,698 --> 01:22:20,428
No, actually, those are the hours
when you work with George.

1169
01:22:21,435 --> 01:22:23,528
Well, no. I mean,
I can be a workaholic too.

1170
01:22:23,704 --> 01:22:28,368
That's why I'm vigilant about separating
my personal and professional life.

1171
01:22:28,542 --> 01:22:32,945
Really? Well, I guess that would explain
the late-night meeting in your slip.

1172
01:22:33,114 --> 01:22:35,674
- I'm sorry?
- What?

1173
01:22:35,850 --> 01:22:37,875
That is absolutely none of your business.

1174
01:22:38,052 --> 01:22:39,952
My God. Fine.
How much does a stapler run?

1175
01:22:40,121 --> 01:22:41,850
Here, here's $10.

1176
01:22:42,022 --> 01:22:43,489
- Ridiculous.
- It's not your stapler.

1177
01:22:43,657 --> 01:22:45,989
What's the matter with you?
Give me my stapler.

1178
01:22:46,160 --> 01:22:47,627
Look. You didn't pay for it.

1179
01:22:47,795 --> 01:22:51,891
- Give me... You have more of these!
- It's not your... Oh, my God.

1180
01:22:53,134 --> 01:22:55,295
- No. No.
- All we're missing is the mud.

1181
01:22:55,469 --> 01:22:57,630
All right. Enough. Enough. Leave.

1182
01:22:57,805 --> 01:23:00,205
- She's hurting me!
- Leave, leave. Off, off.

1183
01:23:00,374 --> 01:23:02,103
In here.

1184
01:23:02,276 --> 01:23:04,335
<i>You are dead!</i>

1185
01:23:07,314 --> 01:23:10,112
- What was that?
- Your girlfriend wouldn't give me my stapler.

1186
01:23:10,284 --> 01:23:13,219
- Part of a new office supply strip search.
- Your stapler?

1187
01:23:13,387 --> 01:23:15,582
Are you still knocking down
the community center?

1188
01:23:16,524 --> 01:23:18,082
Listen.

1189
01:23:18,492 --> 01:23:22,451
- I know you're upset about last night.
- Still knocking down the community center?

1190
01:23:22,630 --> 01:23:25,963
- I've been trying to call you...
- Still knocking down the community center?

1191
01:23:26,133 --> 01:23:29,728
What is wrong with you? Are you
incapable of talking about your own life?

1192
01:23:29,904 --> 01:23:31,929
Still knocking down
the community center?

1193
01:23:32,106 --> 01:23:36,406
All right. Let me remind you.
You came to the hotel.

1194
01:23:36,577 --> 01:23:39,011
I was with June.
We were unusually dressed.

1195
01:23:39,180 --> 01:23:41,671
You must... You must have some feelings.

1196
01:23:48,722 --> 01:23:51,452
I don't have to listen to this.

1197
01:23:52,226 --> 01:23:55,218
You know what, where do you come off?

1198
01:23:55,462 --> 01:23:58,954
Where do you come off? Believe it or not,
I didn't take this job to sleep with you.

1199
01:23:59,133 --> 01:24:01,931
- I took this job for a cause.
- You are a cause!

1200
01:24:02,102 --> 01:24:04,195
You make Gandhi
look like a used-car salesman.

1201
01:24:04,371 --> 01:24:07,863
My God. You know what I can't believe?
How easy you are being on yourself.

1202
01:24:08,042 --> 01:24:12,479
Why don't we go over this again, okay?
You promised me a community center.

1203
01:24:12,646 --> 01:24:15,274
Yes! I promised, I promised, I promised.
I'm sorry.

1204
01:24:15,449 --> 01:24:18,077
I can't control the economy.
I can't control my brother.

1205
01:24:21,853 --> 01:24:23,184
- I think you'll find a lot of people are!
- I'm human!

1206
01:24:27,459 --> 01:24:29,791
None of us can keep up with you.
That's probably why...

1207
01:24:29,962 --> 01:24:32,192
...all those other guys bolted.

1208
01:24:34,266 --> 01:24:36,200
'Cause you're intolerable!

1209
01:24:38,270 --> 01:24:40,238
No one wants to live with a saint.
Saints are boring.

1210
01:24:50,515 --> 01:24:53,313
Mr. Wade, your brother wants to see you.

1211
01:24:55,587 --> 01:24:57,179
Right.

1212
01:25:10,502 --> 01:25:13,096
Hi, Mr. Wong?

1213
01:25:13,272 --> 01:25:17,504
Yes, Lucy Kelson.
Yeah, it's been a long time, huh?

1214
01:25:17,676 --> 01:25:19,541
I'm back at my parents' house.

1215
01:25:19,711 --> 01:25:23,807
It's kind of fun being in my old bedroom
and in the neighb...

1216
01:25:24,049 --> 01:25:29,385
Sorry. Can I have two number sixes...

1217
01:25:29,554 --> 01:25:33,490
...and a number, a number 12?

1218
01:25:33,659 --> 01:25:35,820
Yes, that's for one.

1219
01:25:35,994 --> 01:25:38,292
Always for one.

1220
01:25:38,463 --> 01:25:40,260
Yes. That's it. No.
You know what...

1221
01:25:40,432 --> 01:25:45,131
...just throw in a couple egg rolls
and that would be great.

1222
01:25:50,075 --> 01:25:56,480
For years, Coney Island has been
trying to attract this kind of development.

1223
01:25:57,716 --> 01:26:02,346
Hopefully, Island Towers
is the start of big things to come.

1224
01:26:02,521 --> 01:26:05,149
And now, it is my honor
to introduce to you...

1225
01:26:05,424 --> 01:26:10,691
...one of the men who made this
all possible, George Wade.

1226
01:26:11,596 --> 01:26:15,259
- You look great.
- Go and earn your money, George.

1227
01:26:20,472 --> 01:26:23,464
- Thanks so much.
- Great.

1228
01:26:23,642 --> 01:26:26,907
Thank you very much, Assemblyman Perez.

1229
01:26:28,647 --> 01:26:30,581
Your mom is teaching today...

1230
01:26:30,749 --> 01:26:33,718
...so we'd better grab a bite to eat
and be on our way.

1231
01:26:33,885 --> 01:26:36,945
We have some protesting to do
at the community center.

1232
01:26:37,122 --> 01:26:39,056
I'm not going.

1233
01:26:39,257 --> 01:26:41,282
- What are you talking about?
- I cannot watch...

1234
01:26:41,460 --> 01:26:43,519
...another building get knocked down.

1235
01:26:43,695 --> 01:26:47,426
Hey. We didn't raise you
to sit on the sidelines.

1236
01:26:47,599 --> 01:26:50,932
Ever since you were a little girl,
you fought for what you believed in.

1237
01:26:51,103 --> 01:26:53,697
You were on the White House
Enemies list at 5.

1238
01:26:53,872 --> 01:26:56,898
Dad, I'm not sitting on the sidelines.
I'm going to work.

1239
01:26:57,075 --> 01:26:59,202
What's the point?
The man's not gonna listen to me.

1240
01:26:59,378 --> 01:27:03,075
Besides, you know, he said
some things to me that were just so...

1241
01:27:06,151 --> 01:27:07,550
True.

1242
01:27:07,953 --> 01:27:11,013
Then you change your tactics,
you change your argument.

1243
01:27:11,189 --> 01:27:12,451
You don't give up.

1244
01:27:12,624 --> 01:27:17,652
We didn't give up on civil rights
or equality for women or fair housing.

1245
01:27:18,063 --> 01:27:19,724
Honey.

1246
01:27:20,132 --> 01:27:23,829
As long as people can change,
the world can change.

1247
01:27:24,136 --> 01:27:26,661
Yeah, but what if people can't change?

1248
01:27:30,976 --> 01:27:32,603
Well...

1249
01:27:32,778 --> 01:27:34,803
...let me put it this way.

1250
01:27:35,647 --> 01:27:39,674
I'm sitting here eating a piece
of cheesecake made entirely of soy.

1251
01:27:40,051 --> 01:27:41,484
And I hate it.

1252
01:27:42,554 --> 01:27:44,613
But I'm eating it.

1253
01:27:52,230 --> 01:27:56,223
I'm going to work. Bye. Good luck.

1254
01:28:03,875 --> 01:28:05,467
The law is pretty clear on this.

1255
01:28:05,644 --> 01:28:09,102
If the landlord has not kept up
proper maintenance, he cannot evict you.

1256
01:28:09,281 --> 01:28:10,612
We will help you, Mrs. Munez.

1257
01:28:10,782 --> 01:28:14,775
Let me run and get you some forms
that you can fill out, and we'll get started.

1258
01:28:27,866 --> 01:28:29,629
Well, hello.

1259
01:28:29,901 --> 01:28:33,098
- Hi.
- You don't remember me, do you?

1260
01:28:33,271 --> 01:28:37,298
Polly St. Clair? You interviewed me?
You thought I was having a baby?

1261
01:28:37,476 --> 01:28:40,809
Oh, yes. Yes, Polly. Wow.

1262
01:28:40,979 --> 01:28:42,503
So you work here now.

1263
01:28:42,681 --> 01:28:45,912
- Terrific. How are you?
- Pregnant.

1264
01:28:46,918 --> 01:28:49,648
- I'm not falling for that one again.
- No, I'm really pregnant.

1265
01:28:49,821 --> 01:28:52,722
- You can congratulate me now.
- Polly, I was not born yesterday.

1266
01:28:52,891 --> 01:28:55,189
I'm pregnant!
You want to see the damn sonogram?

1267
01:28:55,360 --> 01:28:57,294
Mrs. Munez, we have two other cases...

1268
01:28:57,462 --> 01:28:59,020
Hi.

1269
01:29:02,167 --> 01:29:04,863
Hi. I'm busy.

1270
01:29:05,437 --> 01:29:07,268
Yes.

1271
01:29:07,572 --> 01:29:10,507
I need your advice on one last thing...

1272
01:29:10,675 --> 01:29:13,109
...and then I promise
you will never hear from me again.

1273
01:29:13,278 --> 01:29:16,839
I just delivered the first speech written
entirely by myself since we met...

1274
01:29:17,015 --> 01:29:23,147
...and I think I may have blown it,
so I wanted to ask your thoughts.

1275
01:29:23,321 --> 01:29:26,290
Okay. Then I will read it to you.

1276
01:29:26,458 --> 01:29:28,949
"I'd like to welcome everyone
on this special day.

1277
01:29:29,127 --> 01:29:31,493
Island Towers will bring prestige
to the neighborhood...

1278
01:29:31,663 --> 01:29:33,494
...and become part
of Brooklyn's renaissance.

1279
01:29:33,665 --> 01:29:35,895
And we're very pleased
and proud to be here.

1280
01:29:36,067 --> 01:29:38,763
Unfortunately,
there is one fly in the ointment.

1281
01:29:38,937 --> 01:29:40,734
You see, I gave my word to someone...

1282
01:29:40,906 --> 01:29:43,875
...that we wouldn't knock down
this building behind me.

1283
01:29:44,042 --> 01:29:47,569
Normally, and those who know me
or were married to me can attest to this...

1284
01:29:47,746 --> 01:29:51,739
...my word wouldn't mean very much.
So why does it this time?

1285
01:29:51,917 --> 01:29:54,784
Well, partly because this building
is an architectural gem...

1286
01:29:54,953 --> 01:29:57,080
...and deserves to be landmarked.

1287
01:29:57,255 --> 01:30:03,091
Partly because people do need a place
to do senior's water ballet and CPR.

1288
01:30:03,261 --> 01:30:05,491
Preferably not together.

1289
01:30:06,598 --> 01:30:11,865
But mainly because this person,
despite being unusually stubborn...

1290
01:30:12,037 --> 01:30:18,442
...and unwilling to compromise
and a very poor dresser, is...

1291
01:30:19,578 --> 01:30:21,443
She's...

1292
01:30:22,547 --> 01:30:26,347
...rather like the building
she loves so much.

1293
01:30:26,518 --> 01:30:31,080
A little rough around the edges,
but when you look closely...

1294
01:30:31,990 --> 01:30:33,821
...absolutely beautiful.

1295
01:30:36,528 --> 01:30:39,224
And the only one of her kind.

1296
01:30:43,735 --> 01:30:47,432
And even though I've said cruel things
and driven her away...

1297
01:30:47,772 --> 01:30:50,104
...she's become the voice in my head.

1298
01:30:52,310 --> 01:30:55,006
And I can't seem to drown her out.

1299
01:30:58,216 --> 01:31:01,083
And I don't want to drown her out.

1300
01:31:04,923 --> 01:31:08,450
So we are going to keep
the community center.

1301
01:31:10,662 --> 01:31:13,529
Because I gave my word to her...

1302
01:31:16,267 --> 01:31:19,293
...and because we gave our word
to the community."

1303
01:31:23,141 --> 01:31:25,234
And I didn't sleep with June.

1304
01:31:26,978 --> 01:31:31,506
That's not in the speech, that's just me
letting you know that important fact.

1305
01:31:34,919 --> 01:31:36,352
What do you think?

1306
01:31:46,097 --> 01:31:48,463
I have to get back to work.

1307
01:31:57,208 --> 01:31:58,698
Right.

1308
01:31:58,910 --> 01:32:02,437
Right, yes, yes, yes. Sorry to disturb.

1309
01:32:08,420 --> 01:32:09,910
Congratulations again, Polly.

1310
01:32:36,381 --> 01:32:40,613
Aside from the split infinitive
that was somewhere in the middle...

1311
01:32:41,786 --> 01:32:44,653
...that speech was actually quite perfect,
wasn't it?

1312
01:32:44,823 --> 01:32:48,759
Yeah. I don't know what the hell
you're still doing sitting here.

1313
01:32:48,927 --> 01:32:51,293
And I don't even like him.

1314
01:33:09,981 --> 01:33:11,676
George!

1315
01:33:34,305 --> 01:33:39,106
George, I just want to say thank you.

1316
01:33:39,544 --> 01:33:42,035
Thank you and I know
I can be harsh and demanding...

1317
01:33:42,213 --> 01:33:45,307
...but I want to try and change
because I believe people can change.

1318
01:33:45,483 --> 01:33:49,579
I can change and not be so demanding
and, you know, like, meet you halfway.

1319
01:33:49,754 --> 01:33:52,814
I just... I know... Things just...

1320
01:33:54,125 --> 01:33:55,922
Once I...

1321
01:33:58,797 --> 01:33:59,957
Lucy...

1322
01:34:00,765 --> 01:34:03,131
...I am in love with you.

1323
01:34:05,770 --> 01:34:08,102
And I'm in love with you.

1324
01:34:16,114 --> 01:34:18,378
Oh, I should just mention
that I have resigned...

1325
01:34:18,883 --> 01:34:21,283
...and am now poor.
- Good.

1326
01:34:21,452 --> 01:34:25,912
When I say poor, I mean we may have to
share a helicopter with another family.

1327
01:34:26,090 --> 01:34:27,751
Does that work for you?

1328
01:34:27,926 --> 01:34:31,555
As long as I don't have to work for you,
we will be fine.

1329
01:34:31,729 --> 01:34:33,356
Excellent.

1330
01:34:34,532 --> 01:34:38,400
And now I would very much like
to discuss that whole bobcat-pretzel thing.

1331
01:34:38,670 --> 01:34:42,401
Oh, I was just kidding.
I'm allergic to bobcats, actually.

1332
01:34:42,674 --> 01:34:44,073
I'm very sorry to hear that.

1333
01:34:45,009 --> 01:34:49,241
- But I can do the pretzel.
- That's excellent news.

1334
01:35:30,922 --> 01:35:32,651
Hi, Mr. Wong, it's Lucy Kelson.

1335
01:35:32,824 --> 01:35:37,523
I need one number 13,
two number sevens...

1336
01:35:37,695 --> 01:35:40,323
I can't believe how small this apartment is.
It's shocking.

1337
01:35:40,498 --> 01:35:46,027
I need three number eights, no garlic.

1338
01:35:46,204 --> 01:35:49,139
It's good your parents went to the movies.
We'd never have squeezed in.

1339
01:35:49,307 --> 01:35:54,609
I need one number seven and...

1340
01:35:54,779 --> 01:35:57,942
I can walk from one side of this apartment
to the other in six seconds.

1341
01:35:58,116 --> 01:36:03,679
- Watch this. One...
- And a number 11, please.

1342
01:36:03,855 --> 01:36:06,346
No, actually this is for two.

1343
01:40:55,947 --> 01:40:56,936
[ ENGLISH ]
